    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1871-02-01T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1871-02-01T00:00:00-05:00" n="385" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d385">
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">No. 364.</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <head>
                    <persName type="from">Mr. Fish</persName> to <persName type="to">General
                            Sickles</persName>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <date calendar="gregorian" when="1871-02-01">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">February</hi> 1, 1871.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>First point in telegram of 30th inadmissible, if construed as forbidding us
                        to question judgments in violation of international law or <pb facs="0979" n="765" xml:id="pg_765"/> of treaty, or if made in the absence of
                        parties. The second and third points seem to exclude naturalized citizens
                        who have not asserted their nationality before Spanish tribunals. My
                        telegram of 28th explains our views. Are these changes, which are
                        inconsistent with telegram of 26th, made for the purpose of delay? Answer,
                        in order that instructions may be given in such case. If Spanish government
                        desire to settle in same manner as in Aspinwall case, why not give Roberts
                        full powers as in that case?</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>FISH.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
